<TITLE> Rift in BJP </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, Mar 17 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The following is a snapshot of recent developments in India's general election campaign. The sources of reports are in brackets. A rift between Arun Jaitley, senior leader of the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), and party president Rajnath Singh has damaged the election campaign of the opposition group. The rift was sparked by the appointment of a controversial businessman to the party campaign. The rift is the latest setback for the BJP, which has struggled to find a popular election platform as well as to tie up coalition deals with allies. (The Hindu, Indian Express) The Communist Party of India (Marxist), India's largest leftist organisation, hinted that it could join a Non-Congress or a non-BJP government after the election. (The Economic Times) "We will see the situation, take stock of it and decide the question," CPI (M) General Secretary Prakash Karat told reporters after the presentation of the party manifesto. After years of blocking economic reforms, the CPI(M) and smaller leftist parties withdrew their support for the government last year to protest against a civilian nuclear deal with the United States. The CPI-(M) held the balance of power for most of the tenure of the Congress Party-led government before withdrawing its support, and has often played a role in shaping coalition government policies
